Executive Summary¶

In China, food and its preparation has been developed so highly that it has reached the status of an art form. Rich and poor, the Chinese people consider that delicious and nutritious food is a basic necessity. There is an old Chinese saying "Food is the first necessity of the people". (Canham, n.d.) History has witnessed the progressions of Chinese cooking in becoming one of the most sought after cuisines worldwide.

This paper aims to examine the characteristics that Chinese restaurants in Chinatown, Las Vegas have in common through the use of a representative-based clustering algorithm and a dimensionality reduction technique. Data for this analysis is obtained from Yelp, an American public company headquartered in San Francisco, California which publishes crowd-sourced reviews about businesses. The study utilized reviews (i.e. text reviews and rating scores) of Chinese Restaurants in the hopes of answering what are the various clusters of Chinese restaurants in Chinatown, Las Vegas and having obtained the clusters, how are these characterized from one another? Before clustering, data was transformed via a TFI-IDF vectorizer which was further processed using singular vector decomposition to reduce dimensionality. With an explained variance threshold at 95%, a total of 1829 features were obtained for clustering.Using a representative-based clustering method which is K-means, an ideal cluster count of k = 4 clusters were identified through eye-baling which was further supported by internal validation results. Conclusively, we found the restaurants are clustered by good experience, noodle soup, dim sum, and pho. We also recommend that current and future Chinese restaurant owners use these clusters and their ratings as a basis for which to strengthen your business and improve areas of it.

Introduction¶

Chinese Cuisine is the broad term of the scrumptious dishes from the various regions and ethnic groups in China. These dishes stood as a legacy of thousands of years of Chinese cooking. It has a long history with superb technology, rich categories, and unique styles that people have taken a liking for. Astoundingly, this manner of cooking is considered to be one of the three world cuisines alongwith French Cuisine and Turkish Cuisine (Top China Travel, n.d.). Its influence has spread not only in Asia but to most parts of the globe, specifically in the United States of America. Historical records had shown that the massive growth of Chinese restaurants in the United States started way back a century ago. According to a research study done by economist Susan Carter, due to passage of the US Immigration Law in the late 20th century, the number of Chinese restaurants doubled from 1910 to 1920, and doubled again from 1920 to 1930. (Godoy, 2016) This entails an established Chinese Community in the U.S. and booming business ecosystem of Chinese cuisine even since then.

A particular community in the U.S which is home to famous restaurants that specializes in Chinese cuisine is found in Chinatown, Las Vegas. Yes, Las Vegas, you heard that right. Aside from the grand neon club parties, high-end dining junctions, and numerous casino betting facilities in famous the Las Vegas Strip, a short drive from the Strip down Spring Mountain Road will put you in Chinatown, a different side of Las Vegas, where you can find mouth-watering meals across a variety of Chinese cuisines for cheaper rates and less pretense. (Kachelriess, 2019) Indeed, doing business in this booming Chinese community is desirable at the very least.

Objective and Metrics¶

This study aims to examine the characteristics that Chinese restaurants in Chinatown, Las Vegas have in common through the use of a representative-based clustering algorithm and a dimensionality reduction technique. More specifically, this paper aims to shed insights to:

  • Businessmen who want to establish their own Chinese Restaurant in the district.
  • Tourists who want to maximize their food exploration journey when to they happen to pass by the area

Scope and Problem Statements¶

The data is obtained from Yelp, an American public company headquartered in San Francisco, California which publishes crowd-sourced reviews about businesses. Primarily, the study utilized reviews (i.e. text reviews and rating scores) of Chinese Restaurants in Chinatown, Las Vegas in the hopes of answering the following queries:

  • What are the various clusters of Chinese restaurants in Chinatown, Las Vegas?
  • Having obtained the clusters, how are these characterized from each other?

# Sentence Cleaner
def sentence_cleaner(text, stop_en=[], 
          punc='!"#$%&\'()+,-./:;<=>?@[\\]^_`{|}~'):
    """Cleans the sentences (remove stopwords, punctuations, etc."""

    comments = re.compile(r'\[[A-Za-z ]+\]')
    punctuations = punc + '…—‘’“”'

    text = comments.sub('', text)


    clean_para = []
    for para in text.split('\n\n\n'):
        clean_sent = []
        for sent in sent_tokenize(re.sub(r'(\s+)', ' ', para)):
            reconst_sent = ' '.join([word for word in 
                                              (sent.lower()
                                                   .translate(
                                                       str.maketrans(
                                                           '',
                                                           '',
                                                           punctuations))
                                                   .split()) 
                                           if word not in stop_en])
            if reconst_sent:
                clean_sent.append(reconst_sent)
        clean_para.append(' '.join(clean_sent))
    # Rejoining as a paragraph
    text = '\n\n\n'.join(clean_para)
    
    return text

# Word Cloud

def word_cloud(word_freq):
    wc = WordCloud(background_color="white", max_words=2000, max_font_size=256,
           random_state=42, width=1000, height=500, colormap='gist_heat')

    wc.generate_from_frequencies(word_freq)

    return wc

def ngrams(text, n=1):
    """Returns the n-gram of the text.

    An 𝑛-gram is a sequence of 𝑛 successive words in a paragraph of text.

    Parameters
    ----------
    n : int
        Number of successive words, default value is 1

    Returns
    -------
    dict
        Dict-like object with the 𝑛-gram string as keys and
        their counts as values

    Examples
    --------
    >>> analyzer = analyzer = PGalyzer(file_path, True)
    >>> analyzer.ngram(2)
    {'produced by': 1,
     'by greg': 1,
     'greg weeks': 1,
     'weeks dave': 1,
     ...}
    """
    # par_list = self.text.split('\n')
    par_list = text.split('\n\n\n')
    n_words = []

    for par in par_list:
        word_list = par.split()
        if len(word_list) >= n:
            for i in range(len(word_list)-n+1):
                n_words.append(' '.join(word_list[i:i+n]))

    # return dict(Counter(n_words))
    return dict(Counter(n_words).most_common())

# Plotting Functions
def scree(variance_explained, thres=0.975):
    """Generates the scree plot and determine minimum number of components
    given a threshold"""
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5,5))

    ax.bar(range(1, len(variance_explained)+1), variance_explained, 
           align='center', label='variance')
    
    ax.set_ylim(0,1)
    ax.set_xlim(0, len(variance_explained)+1)
    ax.set_xlabel('No. of Components (PC for PCA, SV for SVD)')
    ax.set_ylabel('Variance Explained')
    
    lines, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()

    ax = ax.twinx()
    ax.plot(range(1, len(variance_explained)+1), variance_explained.cumsum(), 
            'r-', label='cumulative variance')
    ax.set_ylabel('cumulative variance explained')
    lines2, labels2 = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
    ax.legend(lines+lines2, labels+labels2)

    ax.axhline(thres, ls='--', color='g')
    k_components = sum(variance_explained.cumsum() <= thres)
    ax.axvline(k_components, ls='--', color='g')
    ax.set_title('Scree plot for explained variance\n'
                 f'For threshold = {thres}, k = {k_components}')
    return ax, k_components

def axis_analysis(svd, features):
    """Conducts topic modelling. Looks what comprises each component"""

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 5, figsize=(20, 4))
    features = np.array(features)
    p = svd.components_.T

    for i, ax in enumerate(axes):

        ind = np.argsort(np.abs(p[:, i]))[-10:]
        ax.barh(features[ind], p[ind, i])
        ax.set_title('Topic Models for SV{x} ({y:0.2f}%)'
                        .format(x=i+1, 
                                y=svd.explained_variance_ratio_[i]*100))
        ax.set_xlabel('Magnitude in the SV axis')
        
    plt.tight_layout()

    return ax

# Representative Clustering
class RepresentativeClustering():

    
    def __init__(self, status=True, random_state=1337):
        """Initialization"""
        self.ys = []
        self.inertias = []
        self.chs = []
        self.scs = []
        self.gss = []
        self.gssds = []
        self.ps = []
        self.amis = []
        self.ars = []
        self.results = {}
        self.clusterer = None
        self.start = 2
        self.stop = 5
        self.status = status
        self.random_state = random_state
    
    
    def status_switch(self, switch=True):
        """Turns status on and off"""
        self.status = switch
        return self
    
    
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        """Fit the data"""
        self.X = X
        self.y = y
        
        return self
    
    
    def process(self, clusterer, k_start=2, k_stop=5, 
                      gs=False, scs=False,
                      chs=True, ps=True, amis=True, ars=True, dist=euclidean,
                      random_state=1337, b_fold=5):
        """
        Given a set of parameters, return a dictionary of the cluster labels,
        internal validation values, and if actual labels are given, external
        validation values for every k
        
        Parameters
        ----------
        X : numpy array
            design matrix
        clusteter : object
            clustering object
        k_start: 
            initial value to step through
        k_stop:
            final values to step through 
        actual: list (optional)
            labels, default None
        
        Return
        ------
        dict
            Dictionary containing cluster labels and validation (internal and 
        external) criteria for every k
        """

        self.clusterer = clusterer
        self.start = k_start
        self.stop = k_stop

        X = self.X 
        actual = self.y
        b = b_fold

        random_state = random_state
        
        for i, k in enumerate(range(k_start, k_stop+1)):

            clusterer_k = clone(clusterer)
            clusterer_k.set_params(n_clusters=k, 
                                    random_state=random_state)
        
            y_k = clusterer_k.fit_predict(X)   
        
            self.ys.append(y_k)
            
            self.inertias.append(clusterer_k.inertia_)

            y_k = self.ys[i]

            if chs:
                self.chs.append(calinski_harabasz_score(X, y_k))
                
            if scs:
                self.scs.append(silhouette_score(X, y_k))
                
            if gs:
                gs = self.gap_statistic(X, y_k, clusterer_k.cluster_centers_, 
                                    dist, b, 
                                    clone(clusterer).set_params(n_clusters=k), 
                                    random_state=random_state)
                
                self.gss.append(gs[0])
                self.gssds.append(gs[1])

            if actual is not None:
                if ps:
                    self.ps.append(self.purity(y_true=actual, y_pred=y_k))
                if amis:
                    self.amis.append(adjusted_mutual_info_score(actual, y_k))
                if ars:    
                    self.ars.append(adjusted_rand_score(actual, y_k))

        keys = ['ys', 'inertias', 'chs', 'scs', 'gss', 'gssds', 
                'ps', 'amis', 'ars']

        values = [self.ys, self.inertias, self.chs, self.scs, self.gss, 
                  self.gssds, self.ps, self.amis, self.ars]

        self.results =  {k:v  for k, v in 
                        zip((keys if actual is not None else keys[:-3]), 
                        (values if actual is not None else values[:-3]))}

    def purity(self, y_true, y_pred):
        """Compute the class purity
        
        Parameters
        ----------
        y_true : array
            List of ground-truth labels
        y_pred : array
            Cluster labels
            
        Returns
        -------
        purity : float
            Class purity
        """
        # m_ij where i = y_true, j = y_pred
        cm = confusion_matrix(y_true=y_true, y_pred=y_pred)
        # P_j is the max/ dominant class per cluster j
        # M_j is the sum of datapoints per cluster j
        return cm.max(axis=0).sum()/cm.sum(axis=0).sum()

    
    def export(self, features, k):
        """Export the clustering results by appending to features DataFrame"""
        
        return (pd.DataFrame(features, 
                             columns=features.columns.to_list())
                  .join(pd.DataFrame(self.ys[k-self.start], 
                                     columns=['cluster'])))


    def plot_clusters(self, X=None):
        """Plot clusters given the design matrix and cluster labels"""

        X = self.X[:, 0:2] if X is None else X

        ys = self.ys 
        #+ 1 from the effect of range generator above. Assumes starts with 2
        k_max = len(ys) + 1  
        k_mid = k_max//2 + 2

        fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, k_max//2, sharex=True, sharey=True, 
                            figsize=(20,8) , subplot_kw=dict(aspect='equal'),
                            gridspec_kw=dict(wspace=0.01))
        
        for k,y in zip(range(2, k_max+1), ys):
            if k < k_mid:
                ax[0][k%k_mid-2].scatter(*zip(*X), c=y, s=1, alpha=0.8)
                ax[0][k%k_mid-2].set_title('$k=%d$'%k)
            else:
                ax[1][k%k_mid].scatter(*zip(*X), c=y, s=1, alpha=0.8)
                ax[1][k%k_mid].set_title('$k=%d$'%k)

        return ax


    def plot_internal(self):
        """Plot internal validation values"""

        inertias = self.inertias 
        chs = self.chs
        scs = self.scs
        gss = self.gss
        gssds = self.gssds

        fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=3, figsize=(15,5))
        ks = np.arange(self.start, self.stop + 1)

        ax[0].plot(ks, inertias, '-o', label='SSE')
        ax[0].plot(ks, chs, '-ro', label='CH')

        
        lines, labels = ax[0].get_legend_handles_labels()
        
        ax[1].set_ylabel('Gap statistic/Silhouette')

        try:
            ax[1].errorbar(ks, gss, gssds, fmt='-go', label='Gap statistic')
            ax[2].errorbar(ks, gss, gssds, fmt='-go', label='Gap statistic')
            ax[1].plot(ks, scs, '-ko', label='Silhouette coefficient')
            lines2, labels2 = ax[1].get_legend_handles_labels()
            ax[1].legend(lines+lines2, labels+labels2)
        except Exception:
            ax[1].legend(lines, labels)
            pass

        ax[0].set_title('SSD and Calinsky-Harabazs Score')
        ax[1].set_title('Gap Statistic and Silhouette Score')
        ax[2].set_title('Gap Statistic (close-up)')
        ax[1].set_xlabel('$k$')
        ax[2].set_xlabel('$k$')
        ax[0].set_ylabel('SSE/CH')
        ax[1].set_ylabel('GS/SC')
        ax[2].set_ylabel('Gap Statistic')

        plt.tight_layout()
        
        return ax

    
    def plot_external(self):
        """Plot external validation values"""

        ps = self.ps
        amis = self.amis
        ars = self.ars

        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5,5))
        ks = np.arange(self.start, self.stop+1)
        ax.plot(ks, ps, '-o', label='PS')
        ax.plot(ks, amis, '-ro', label='AMI')
        ax.plot(ks, ars, '-go', label='AR')
        ax.set_xlabel('$k$')
        ax.set_ylabel('PS/AMI/AR')
        ax.set_title('External Validation Criteria')
        ax.legend()
        
        return ax

    
    def gap_statistic(self, X, y, centroids, dist, b, clusterer, 
                      random_state=None):
        """Compute the gap statistic
        
        Parameters
        ----------
        X : array
            Design matrix with each row corresponding to a point
        y : array
            Class label of each point
        centroids : array
            Number of pairs to sample
        dist : callable
            Distance between two points. It should accept two arrays, each 
            corresponding to the coordinates of each point
        b : int
            Number of realizations for the reference distribution
        clusterer : KMeans
            Clusterer object that will be used for clustering the reference 
            realizations
        random_state : int, default=None
            Determines random number generation for realizations
            
        Returns
        -------
        gs : float
            Gap statistic
        gs_std : float
            Standard deviation of gap statistic
        """
        
        rng = np.random.default_rng(random_state)
        max_x = np.max(X, axis=0)
        min_x = np.min(X, axis=0)

        # Obtain the pooled within ssd of the given data
        wk = self.pooled_within_ssd(X, y, centroids, dist)
        
        wk_i = []
        for _ in range(b):
            # Each realization b will have a unique y_i, centroids_i,
            # We need to initialize the clusterer every time then predict 
            # y_i by
            # fitting X_i. Obtain the new centroids using the cluster_centers_ 
            # attrib.

            X_i = rng.uniform(min_x, max_x, size=X.shape)
            clusterer_i = clone(clusterer)
            clusterer_i.set_params(n_clusters=len(centroids))
            y_i = clusterer_i.fit_predict(X_i)
            centroids_i = clusterer_i.cluster_centers_
            wk_i.append(self.pooled_within_ssd(X_i, y_i, centroids_i, dist))
            
        return [np.mean(np.log(wk_i))-np.log(wk), np.std(np.log(wk_i))]


    def pooled_within_ssd(self, X, y, centroids, dist):
        """Compute pooled within-cluster sum of squares around the cluster
        mean
        
        Parameters
        ----------
        X : array
            Design matrix with each row corresponding to a point
        y : array
            Class label of each point
        centroids : array
            Number of pairs to sample
        dist : callable
            Distance between two points. It should accept two arrays, each 
            corresponding to the coordinates of each point
            
        Returns
        -------
        float
            Pooled within-cluster sum of squares around the cluster mean
        """

        return sum([(dist(x_i, centroids[y_i])**2) /(2*(y==y_i).sum())
                    for x_i, y_i in zip(X, y.astype(int))])

# Pooled with SSD
def pooled_within_ssd(X, y, centroids, dist):
    """Compute pooled within-cluster sum of squares around the cluster mean
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    X : array
        Design matrix with each row corresponding to a point
    y : array
        Class label of each point
    centroids : array
        Number of pairs to sample
    dist : callable
        Distance between two points. It should accept two arrays, each 
        corresponding to the coordinates of each point
        
    Returns
    -------
    float
        Pooled within-cluster sum of squares around the cluster mean
    """
    y = y.astype(int)
    total = np.bincount(y)
    result = 0
    
    for x, y in zip (X, y):
        result += (dist(x, centroids[y])**2/(2*total[y]))
    
    return result

# Gap Statistic
def gap_statistic(X, y, centroids, dist, b, clusterer, random_state=None):
    """Compute the gap statistic
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    X : array
        Design matrix with each row corresponding to a point
    y : array
        Class label of each point
    centroids : array
        Number of pairs to sample
    dist : callable
        Distance between two points. It should accept two arrays, each 
        corresponding to the coordinates of each point
    b : int
        Number of realizations for the reference distribution
    clusterer : KMeans
        Clusterer object that will be used for clustering the reference 
        realizations
    random_state : int, default=None
        Determines random number generation for realizations
        
    Returns
    -------
    gs : float
        Gap statistic
    gs_std : float
        Standard deviation of gap statistic
    """
    rng = np.random.default_rng(random_state)
    
    ssd = np.log(pooled_within_ssd(X, y, centroids, dist))
    stats = np.array([])
    
    for i in range(b):
        X_i = rng.uniform(low = X.min(0), high = X.max(0), size = X.shape)
        y_i = clusterer.fit_predict(X_i)
        ssd_i = np.log(pooled_within_ssd(X_i, y_i,
                                         clusterer.cluster_centers_, dist))
        stats = np.append(stats, (ssd_i - ssd))
        
    return stats.mean(),stats.std()
In [9]:
# Cluster Range
def cluster_range(X, clusterer, k_start, k_stop, actual=None):
    ys = []
    inertias = []
    chs = []
    scs = []
    gss = []
    gssds = []
    ps = []
    amis = []
    ars = []
    for k in range(k_start, k_stop+1):
        clusterer_k = clone(clusterer)
        clusterer_k.set_params(n_clusters = k)
        y = clusterer_k.fit_predict(X)
        
        ys += [y]
        inertias += [clusterer_k.inertia_]
        chs += [calinski_harabasz_score(X,y)]
        scs += [silhouette_score(X,y)]
        
        if actual is not None:
            ps += [purity(actual, y)]
            amis += [adjusted_mutual_info_score(actual, y)]
            ars += [adjusted_rand_score(actual, y)]
            
        
        gs = gap_statistic(X, y, clusterer_k.cluster_centers_, 
                                 euclidean, 5, 
                                 clone(clusterer).set_params(n_clusters=k), 
                                 random_state=1337)
        
        gss.append(gs[0])
        gssds.append(gs[1])
        
    result = {'ys':ys, 'inertias':inertias, 'chs':chs,
              'gss':gss, 'gssds':gssds, 'scs':scs}
    
    if actual is not None:
        result['ps'] = ps
        result['amis'] = amis
        result['ars'] = ars
        
    return result

# Plot Clusters
def plot_clusters(X, ys):
    """Plot clusters given the design matrix and cluster labels"""
    k_max = len(ys) + 1
    k_mid = k_max//2 + 2
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, k_max//2, dpi=150, sharex=True, sharey=True, 
                           figsize=(7,4), subplot_kw=dict(aspect='equal'),
                           gridspec_kw=dict(wspace=0.01))
    for k,y in zip(range(2, k_max+1), ys):
        if k < k_mid:
            ax[0][k%k_mid-2].scatter(*zip(*X), c=y, s=1, alpha=0.8)
            ax[0][k%k_mid-2].set_title('$k=%d$'%k)
        else:
            ax[1][k%k_mid].scatter(*zip(*X), c=y, s=1, alpha=0.8)
            ax[1][k%k_mid].set_title('$k=%d$'%k)
    return ax

def plot_internal(inertias, chs, scs, gss, gssds):
    """Plot internal validation values"""
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ks = np.arange(2, len(inertias)+2)
    ax.plot(ks, inertias, '-o', label='SSE')
    ax.plot(ks, chs, '-ro', label='CH')
    ax.set_xlabel('$k$')
    ax.set_ylabel('SSE/CH')
    lines, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
    ax2 = ax.twinx()
    ax2.errorbar(ks, gss, gssds, fmt='-go', label='Gap statistic')
    ax2.plot(ks, scs, '-ko', label='Silhouette coefficient')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Gap statistic/Silhouette')
    lines2, labels2 = ax2.get_legend_handles_labels()
    ax2.legend(lines+lines2, labels+labels2)
    return ax

from wordcloud import WordCloud

def word_cloud(word_freq):
    wc = WordCloud(background_color="white", max_words=2000, max_font_size=256,
           random_state=42, width=1000, height=500, colormap='gist_heat')

    wc.generate_from_frequencies(word_freq)

    return wc

Truncated SVD¶

To further reduce our dataset into the most meaningful words for our analysis, we perform a Truncated SVD. Using the bag of words with maximum $n$-grams of 4 and with an explained variance threshold of 0.95, we obtain a k of 1829.

In [26]:
svd = TruncatedSVD(n_components=text_bow4.shape[1]-1, random_state=1337)
svd.fit(text_bow4)

ax, k = scree(svd.explained_variance_ratio_, thres=0.95);

Fitting our data to the SVD with n_components equal to 1829 as acquired above, we ultimately arrive with an explained variance of 94.85%.

$k$-means Representative-Based Clustering¶

With the features identified above, we now use $k$-means in order to identify the clusters from our dataset.

In [30]:
kmeans_sent = RepresentativeClustering().fit(X=X_sent)
kmeans_sent.process(clusterer=KMeans(random_state=1337), k_start=2, k_stop=11, 
          dist=euclidean, gs=True, scs=True)
In [31]:
ax = kmeans_sent.plot_clusters();
plt.suptitle('Cluster plots of the review word corpus using various k\n'
             'Graphs are in the SV2-SV1 plane');

Given the figures above, the ideal number of clusters is difficult to determine. However, we can see that for k's 5 or less, the clusters are:

  • Compact: points in the same cluster are close together with the following exceptions where there are noticeable outliers for k = 2 and k = 3, and an unidentifiable cluster for k = 4 and k = 5.
  • Parsimonious: with k of 5 or less, we minimize the number of clusters while obtaining a meaningful interpretation.

To further guide us in choosing the ideal k from those mentioned above, we now investigate their internal validations.

Using the elbow method in determining the ideal k, we used both SSD and gap statistic as our validation measures. It is clear from the gap statistic that from the choices previously narrowed down, k = 4 is ideal.

In [33]:
ax = kmeans_sent.plot_internal();

In order for us to clearly distinguish the point at which the elbow is determined, we compute for the following values where for each k, its difference from the SSD value of the prior k is maximized while the difference from the next k is minimized:

In [34]:

                'after': after,

It is fortunate that the cluster with the lowest ratings also has the least number of reviews, i.e. Cluster 2, our Chinese ancestors will be disappointed to know that this cluster is characterized by the word dim sum. However, the presence of pho is still evident in Cluster 0. All clusters are characterized as follows:

Cluster 0: Good Experience It is characteristic of traditional Chinese restaurants to have the best cuisine while needing work on improving customer experience such as the place or the service. However, this cluster seems to have a characterically decent performance on such aspects with an average rating of 3.5 stars.

Cluster 1: Noodle Soup Champions Who cannot associate noodle soups to Chinese restaurants? True to this dish being part of a hearty meal, whether one prefers chicken, pork, or beef to go with it, this cluster definitely champions not just this dish in their menu but also the other restaurants by getting the highest average rating of 3.8 stars.

Cluster 2: Dim Sum Cart Haven To those who aren't familiar with the authentic Chinese restaurant experience, dim sum being served in carts may test their patience. And the customer's impatience may also affect the mood of our servers bringing the cart around the restaurant. So, while it's reasonable for this cluster to have the lowest average rating of 3.1 stars due to logistics, if they want the authentic Chinese experience of having freshly prepared and steamed dimsum, then this cluster is the way to go.

Cluster 3: Pho-sion (Fusion) Cuisine? Understandably, Vietnam was occupied by Chinese dynasties, but this was already ended many hundreds of years ago. While we have nothing against fusion cuisine, Vietnamese cuisine is already very much alike to some Chinese dishes that makes up any rice noodles or spring rolls. This may be the reason why this cluster of reviews identified thick rice noodle soups as pho dishes. Otherwise, if certain Chinese restaurant owners have started to include pho in their menus then the ancestors will definitely be disappointed. We will not even speak of the decent average rating this cluster got (but it's 3.6 stars).

Conclusion and Recommendation¶

For tourists who will decide to visit Las Vegas, we encourage you to try the various food from the various clusters that we have identified in this study. Aside from maximizing your experience by trying out how the different kinds of Chinese cuisine has been adapated to the palatte of Las Vegas, you also will be helping business owners by adding to the insights they get from a more enriched quality of reviews with your new points of view.

For businessmen who want to establish their own Chinese Restaurant in the district, we understand that you want to assimilate different cultures into your own such as the similar Vietnamese national dish of pho. However, we suggest that you make our ancestors proud by strengthening the brand of Chinese cuisine and avoid association with other culture's dishes. For those who will offer rice noodle dishes in their menu, we encourage you to give it a Chinese name and start to market it as such. Moreover, the average rating of each cluster may be used as a guide on which aspects of a Chinese restaurant to focus your resources on. And if you currently own a Chinese restaurant, then the ratings may also serve as a guide for which aspects you can improve on. If you still want the challenge of handling dim sum in your menu, then we definitely recommend having enough carts to cater to the number of seats occupied in the restaurant at any given time such that there will be less waiting time for customers.

But who knew that Chinese cuisine will become a big hit in Las Vegas, right? Who would have thought 'muricans will know of dim sum, noodle soup, or spring rolls? Those who have paved the way for the spread of Chinese culture: you make our ancestors proud.
